1
00:00:03,559 --> 00:00:04,628
I like your suit.

2
00:00:04,839 --> 00:00:07,194
Oh, thanks.
Got a couple new outfits for work.

3
00:00:07,400 --> 00:00:09,755
How's it feel knowing your fiancé's job
is to go out...

4
00:00:09,920 --> 00:00:11,797
...and flirt with doctors looking like that...

5
00:00:11,999 --> 00:00:15,514
...while you sit here,
you know, looking like this?

6
00:00:16,800 --> 00:00:20,156
-She doesn't flirt with doctors.
-Yeah. It's all very professional.

7
00:00:20,359 --> 00:00:21,394
When you bend over...

8
00:00:21,559 --> 00:00:23,834
-...I can see down your shirt.
-Okay, good.

9
00:00:25,439 --> 00:00:28,272
Speaking of new careers,
how are things going with dark matter?

10
00:00:28,599 --> 00:00:32,478
Oh. Yeah. I'd have to say it's the most
exciting time in the history of the field.

11
00:00:32,679 --> 00:00:34,192
Oh. What's going on?

12
00:00:34,399 --> 00:00:35,957
I started doing it.

13
00:00:36,839 --> 00:00:39,353
You know the government funded
the biggest experiment yet...

14
00:00:39,520 --> 00:00:41,112
...to detect dark matter?

15
00:00:41,319 --> 00:00:44,914
I read about that. They're sending research
teams down into abandoned salt mines.

16
00:00:45,120 --> 00:00:47,554
Look. Sheldon, if we apply
to be one of those teams...

17
00:00:47,760 --> 00:00:50,035
...we could be on the ground floor
of something big.

18
00:00:50,239 --> 00:00:52,628
Not just for theoretical physics,
but for astrophysics.

19
00:00:52,839 --> 00:00:53,828
Hang on.

20
00:00:54,039 --> 00:00:56,269
-You guys are gonna work in a mine?
-Why not?

21
00:00:56,880 --> 00:00:59,519
You had a panic attack
when we went through the car wash.

22
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:04,596
Perhaps the emotion you're referring to
was shock at you having something cleaned.

23
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:09,310
I think what Penny meant is the thought
of you two in a mine is funny.

24
00:01:09,519 --> 00:01:11,475
It's like a cat riding a Roomba.

25
00:01:12,719 --> 00:01:14,869
If they get scared,
they'll have hats with lights...

26
00:01:15,040 --> 00:01:18,237
...because down there,
it's night-night all the time.

27
00:01:19,399 --> 00:01:21,788
Maybe they can ride around
in one of those mine cars that go:

28
00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:23,518
[MIMICS SQUEAKING]

29
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:27,595
That'll help them get away
when they see a g-g-ghost.

30
00:01:27,760 --> 00:01:29,193
[LAUGHS]

31
00:01:29,360 --> 00:01:31,078
-Are they making fun of us?
-Yup.

32
00:01:31,280 --> 00:01:33,635
I miss the old days when I couldn't tell.

33
00:01:58,880 --> 00:02:02,839
So one of my favorite video games of
all time is called "Shadow of the Colossus."

34
00:02:03,039 --> 00:02:04,677
It was only for PlayStation 2...

35
00:02:04,880 --> 00:02:08,156
...but then they came out with a new version
for P53 with better graphics.

36
00:02:08,359 --> 00:02:12,637
I finally got a chance to play it, and for some
reason, it just wasn't as good as the first one.

37
00:02:17,120 --> 00:02:19,634
Or something about yoga.

38
00:02:20,680 --> 00:02:22,477
I'm sorry. I was thinking about work.

39
00:02:22,680 --> 00:02:24,796
Oh, I was just saying
there's this video game--

40
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:27,150
Yeah. That's when I started
thinking about work.

41
00:02:27,760 --> 00:02:29,512
Uh, listen. I've got some good news.

42
00:02:31,640 --> 00:02:34,518
-This is for you.
-Oh.

43
00:02:38,040 --> 00:02:39,758
-What is this?
-You know how they gave me...

44
00:02:39,919 --> 00:02:40,908
...the company car?

45
00:02:41,079 --> 00:02:43,639
Didn't make sense to have
two, so I sold the other one.

46
00:02:43,840 --> 00:02:45,034
-The one I gave you?
-Yeah.

47
00:02:45,240 --> 00:02:47,151
And there's your money back.
Now we're even.

48
00:02:47,359 --> 00:02:49,270
How great is that?

49
00:02:50,360 --> 00:02:52,157
Uh,yeah.

50
00:02:52,439 --> 00:02:53,792
What?

51
00:02:54,079 --> 00:02:55,068
Nothing.

52
00:02:55,279 --> 00:02:58,874
Oh. I know the car was a thoughtful gesture.
I really appreciate it.

53
00:02:59,079 --> 00:03:02,037
-But it doesn't make sense to have both.
-You're right.

54
00:03:02,239 --> 00:03:04,992
What should I have done?
Taken a picture of us in the car...

55
00:03:05,200 --> 00:03:09,830
...put it in a pink frame with puffy paint
around it that says, "Best fiancé ever"?

56
00:03:11,999 --> 00:03:13,557
Doesn't sound that bad.

57
00:03:14,040 --> 00:03:16,076
Well, good, because that's what I did.

58
00:03:16,240 --> 00:03:17,958
Oh, ha, ha.

59
00:03:19,880 --> 00:03:22,235
Thank you. That is so sweet.

60
00:03:22,440 --> 00:03:26,035
Ah, it's not that sweet. I paid for the frame
with your money and then got a massage.

61
00:03:27,600 --> 00:03:30,637
You know what, you don't have to
give me this. You keep it.

62
00:03:30,999 --> 00:03:32,557
-Why?
-The car was a gift.

63
00:03:32,760 --> 00:03:34,751
Something you needed.
I was happy to help you.

64
00:03:35,159 --> 00:03:39,596
And I really appreciate it,
but now I don't need it. So here you go.

65
00:03:39,800 --> 00:03:43,076
This is silly. You don't need the car,
but you could buy something else...

66
00:03:43,279 --> 00:03:46,749
...like a new purse to put all this money in.

67
00:03:47,279 --> 00:03:49,839
Sweetie, I can buy my own stuff.
I have a good job now.

68
00:03:50,040 --> 00:03:55,114
I know, and I'm proud of you, but that doesn't
mean I can't do something nice. Like this.

69
00:03:56,080 --> 00:03:57,513
I don't want this to be a fight.

70
00:03:57,680 --> 00:04:00,752
-I don't either.
-Great. Thank you.

71
00:04:03,559 --> 00:04:05,197
-Can you pass the salt, please?
-Sure.

72
00:04:11,840 --> 00:04:15,799
In my mind, that broke the tension
with comedy and led to sex.

73
00:04:21,479 --> 00:04:22,832
Hey, Sheldon. You busy?

74
00:04:23,239 --> 00:04:24,592
I'm always busy.

75
00:04:24,799 --> 00:04:27,836
This mind is capable
of advanced multi-tasking.

76
00:04:28,199 --> 00:04:31,316
Currently, I'm attempting to solve
the Penrose conjecture.

77
00:04:31,519 --> 00:04:35,956
I'm composing my Nobel acceptance speech
for when I've solved the Penrose conjecture.

78
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:39,118
And I'm wondering
how mermaids have babies.

79
00:04:40,840 --> 00:04:42,910
Don't they lay eggs on a rock?

80
00:04:45,440 --> 00:04:47,954
Now I've got room for another thing.
What do you want?

81
00:04:48,879 --> 00:04:52,554
So I did a little research on
what the conditions are like in the mines.

82
00:04:52,759 --> 00:04:55,068
The guys might be right.
Sounds rough down there.

83
00:04:55,280 --> 00:04:58,716
For starters, it's very humid
and about a hundred degrees.

84
00:04:58,919 --> 00:05:01,638
Well, I'm from Texas, and you're from India.

85
00:05:01,839 --> 00:05:05,388
We're no strangers
to the fragrant armpit. Next.

86
00:05:06,879 --> 00:05:10,554
It's also a live mine so there'll be dynamite
explosions going off in the distance.

87
00:05:10,720 --> 00:05:15,714
Yeah. I have a lactose-intolerant
roommate with a taste for ice cream. Next.

88
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:18,639
Oh, you have to be down there
for 12 hours at a time.

89
00:05:19,080 --> 00:05:21,230
We have to be somewhere.

90
00:05:21,599 --> 00:05:24,113
No toilet, so we'll have to do our business
in a bucket.

91
00:05:24,319 --> 00:05:26,833
So it's settled. We're not doing it.

92
00:05:28,799 --> 00:05:30,118
Look. I get it, but...

93
00:05:30,319 --> 00:05:32,594
...before we pass up
on an incredible opportunity...

94
00:05:32,799 --> 00:05:35,791
...l was thinking about when Howard
was training to go into space...

95
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:39,356
-...they put him in a simulated environment.
-lnteresting.

96
00:05:39,560 --> 00:05:42,518
You're suggesting that we recreate
the conditions of the mine...

97
00:05:42,680 --> 00:05:43,874
...to see if we can handle it.

98
00:05:44,079 --> 00:05:45,876
-Exactly.
-Very well.

99
00:05:46,079 --> 00:05:48,752
-So where should we do it?
-Well, I'll just Google...

100
00:05:48,959 --> 00:05:52,110
..."hot, dark and moist."
See what comes up.

101
00:05:54,440 --> 00:05:57,830
-Uh, Sheldon--
-Look. There's all kinds of videos.

102
00:06:00,560 --> 00:06:01,788
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

103
00:06:01,959 --> 00:06:04,109
-Hey, you got a sec?
-Hi. Sure.

104
00:06:04,319 --> 00:06:07,868
-l was hoping we could talk about the money.
-Oh, sweetie. Just forget about it.

105
00:06:08,080 --> 00:06:10,514
No. Hear me out.
I know things got weird last night.

106
00:06:10,720 --> 00:06:16,113
Well, leaving an envelope full of cash on my
dresser after sex would count as weird.

107
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:20,468
Well, I think I came up
with a pretty good solution.

108
00:06:20,679 --> 00:06:22,715
Why don't we put the money
in ajoint account?

109
00:06:22,919 --> 00:06:26,468
It'll be our first money together. We
can use it for the wedding, the honeymoon.

110
00:06:26,679 --> 00:06:28,317
Yeah. That's great. I love that.

111
00:06:28,519 --> 00:06:31,829
Of course you do.
I'm notjust a genius in bed.

112
00:06:39,400 --> 00:06:41,595
[IN HIGH PITCH VOICE]
"You sure are, baby."

113
00:06:43,560 --> 00:06:45,357
You two wanna be alone?

114
00:06:45,919 --> 00:06:48,308
I want you to know I get why
you don't want the money.

115
00:06:48,480 --> 00:06:51,358
The newjob. You're excited
about being financially independent.

116
00:06:51,559 --> 00:06:53,277
lam nothing but proud of you.

117
00:06:53,480 --> 00:06:56,597
Oh, thank you so much.
It feels so good to hear you say that.

118
00:06:56,799 --> 00:07:00,917
I want you to know that I get this job
changes the balance in our relationship.

119
00:07:01,120 --> 00:07:03,156
And I'm trying to be sensitive to that.

120
00:07:05,959 --> 00:07:07,597
What?

121
00:07:08,399 --> 00:07:12,392
Well, I just think that you're hung up on the
money because I'm less reliant on you now...

122
00:07:12,600 --> 00:07:14,352
...and that's a little scary.

123
00:07:14,839 --> 00:07:16,238
Hmm.

124
00:07:17,679 --> 00:07:19,032
Maybe.

125
00:07:19,880 --> 00:07:23,077
Or maybe I tried to do something nice...

126
00:07:23,279 --> 00:07:27,272
...and maybe you had a problem with it
because of your control issues.

127
00:07:29,399 --> 00:07:30,832
"Control issues."

128
00:07:31,679 --> 00:07:33,237
Maybe.

129
00:07:34,239 --> 00:07:35,957
Or maybe...

130
00:07:36,159 --> 00:07:39,947
...now that I'm no longer an out-of-work
actress who can't pay for her own dinner...

131
00:07:40,159 --> 00:07:41,831
...that makes you a little insecure.

132
00:07:42,200 --> 00:07:46,432
I can't believe you'd say that. You know
how insecure I am about my insecurities.

133
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:51,719
You know what, I'm sorry.
It's stupid to fight over money.

134
00:07:51,919 --> 00:07:55,116
I'm sorry too. We're about to share
the rest of our lives together.

135
00:07:55,320 --> 00:07:57,276
It's our money. Who cares who has it?

136
00:07:57,440 --> 00:08:00,000
Ugh. You're right. Who cares?

137
00:08:01,480 --> 00:08:04,916
Get that money out of my back pocket,
or I'll break your fingers.

138
00:08:07,279 --> 00:08:10,430
Huh. I never knew there were
steam tunnels down here.

139
00:08:10,640 --> 00:08:12,437
Most universities have them.

140
00:08:12,639 --> 00:08:16,268
When lwas an undergrad, I spent
three days in one pledging a sorority.

141
00:08:18,519 --> 00:08:20,635
-Did you get in?
-No. They forgot I was there...

142
00:08:20,839 --> 00:08:22,875
...but it really opened up my pores.

143
00:08:24,559 --> 00:08:26,038
According to my research...

144
00:08:26,240 --> 00:08:31,792
...the steam tunnels below this access point
should be the closest analog to the mines.

145
00:08:31,960 --> 00:08:34,190
It'll be more accurate
than the steam room at the gym.

146
00:08:34,400 --> 00:08:38,075
Plus there's almost no chance
we'll see any of our co-workers half-naked.

147
00:08:38,919 --> 00:08:40,147
Or totally naked.

148
00:08:40,359 --> 00:08:43,192
I love Howard,
but the dude needs a little shame.

149
00:08:43,919 --> 00:08:46,513
Amy, this walkie-talkie is yours.

150
00:08:46,720 --> 00:08:48,836
If we run into any problems, I'll contact you.

151
00:08:49,040 --> 00:08:50,996
If anything bad happens, what's the rule?

152
00:08:51,199 --> 00:08:54,350
Save you first,
come back for Raj only if there's time.

153
00:08:55,319 --> 00:08:56,911
We're going to be fine.

154
00:08:57,079 --> 00:08:58,068
[SHELDON EXHALES SHARPLY]

155
00:08:58,240 --> 00:09:00,470
Sheldon, I'm really impressed
you're willing to try this.

156
00:09:00,680 --> 00:09:04,309
Admittedly, this brushes up against
my well-known aversions to heat...

157
00:09:04,520 --> 00:09:06,909
...small places, going below floor level...

158
00:09:07,079 --> 00:09:11,038
...dampness, hatches, ladders,
darkness, echoes...

159
00:09:11,240 --> 00:09:14,312
...and eliminating in Home Depot buckets.

160
00:09:14,520 --> 00:09:16,750
That last one is quite new,
but I have a feeling...

161
00:09:16,920 --> 00:09:18,990
......that's gonna rocket
to the top of the list.

162
00:09:28,519 --> 00:09:31,033
RAJ:
I'm sweating already.

163
00:09:31,639 --> 00:09:35,518
As the person beneath you,
allow me to say, "I know."

164
00:09:39,760 --> 00:09:42,149
-How hot is it?
-Let's see.

165
00:09:42,360 --> 00:09:45,875
Seven-hundred and four--?
No. Wait. it's on "clock."

166
00:09:46,520 --> 00:09:50,308
Uh, the real answer isn't much better,
102 degrees.

167
00:09:50,680 --> 00:09:53,399
That's what we wanted.
This is as hot as the mines will be.

168
00:09:53,600 --> 00:09:54,999
True.

169
00:09:55,519 --> 00:09:59,478
Sheldon's mine-simulation log. Entry one.

170
00:09:59,680 --> 00:10:04,117
Koothrappali's restating of the obvious
is already getting on my nerves.

171
00:10:07,120 --> 00:10:09,076
-Thanks again for having us.
-Of course.

172
00:10:09,279 --> 00:10:10,792
What did you wanna talk about?

173
00:10:10,999 --> 00:10:12,751
Well, now that we're engaged...

174
00:10:12,920 --> 00:10:16,071
...we had questions about
how you handle money as a couple.

175
00:10:16,639 --> 00:10:19,233
I told you they weren't gonna
ask us to swing with them.

176
00:10:21,680 --> 00:10:23,238
I didn't think they were going to.

177
00:10:23,439 --> 00:10:26,795
I just wanted to have a way to say no
without hurting Leonard's feelings.

178
00:10:27,439 --> 00:10:30,033
Well, nailed it.

179
00:10:30,240 --> 00:10:31,468
What did you wanna know?

180
00:10:31,879 --> 00:10:34,313
Well, do you guys ever fight over money?

181
00:10:34,519 --> 00:10:35,793
Sure. Sometimes.

182
00:10:35,999 --> 00:10:39,275
It can be a little awkward since
I make so much more money than Howie.

183
00:10:41,199 --> 00:10:43,349
You didn't have to say, "So much more."
Heh.

184
00:10:43,600 --> 00:10:46,717
I didn't have to, but for the sake of accuracy,
I felt that I should.

185
00:10:48,040 --> 00:10:50,474
I brought significant assets
into the relationship too.

186
00:10:50,680 --> 00:10:54,639
Like what? Your incomplete set
of Star Trek collector plates?

187
00:10:55,999 --> 00:10:58,957
For your information,
ljust bought the last one I needed on eBay.

188
00:10:59,439 --> 00:11:00,872
Without asking me?

189
00:11:02,120 --> 00:11:04,315
There were only three minutes
left in the auction.

190
00:11:04,519 --> 00:11:07,795
It was a mint-condition
"Scotty" from a smoke-free home.

191
00:11:10,279 --> 00:11:11,951
-How much, Howie?
-Not a lot.

192
00:11:12,159 --> 00:11:13,831
How much?

193
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:16,914
Let's not talk about this
in front of our friends.

194
00:11:17,439 --> 00:11:20,078
Was it more or less than falconry school?

195
00:11:21,600 --> 00:11:25,149
For the 10th time, that was a Groupon.

196
00:11:27,399 --> 00:11:29,037
Like I would swing with him.

197
00:11:34,159 --> 00:11:35,478
How you feeling?

198
00:11:35,679 --> 00:11:36,668
Good.

199
00:11:37,560 --> 00:11:39,437
A little claustrophobic.

200
00:11:39,639 --> 00:11:43,188
Let's set up the equipment.
It'll help take your mind off of it.

201
00:11:43,400 --> 00:11:46,870
Miners often sing mining songs
to keep their spirits up.

202
00:11:47,079 --> 00:11:50,355
-Do you know any mining songs?
-Just the hits.

203
00:11:51,879 --> 00:11:56,475
[SINGING] Where it's dark as a dungeon
And as damp as the dew

204
00:11:56,680 --> 00:11:57,669
That's pretty.

205
00:11:57,880 --> 00:12:03,000
Where the dangers are double
And the pleasures are few

206
00:12:03,199 --> 00:12:07,954
Where the rain never falls
And the sun never shines

207
00:12:08,160 --> 00:12:12,756
Yes, it's dark as a dungeon
Way down in the mines

208
00:12:12,960 --> 00:12:15,030
It's a little more bleak than I thought.

209
00:12:15,279 --> 00:12:19,875
Well, [play when I'm dead
And the ages shall roll

210
00:12:20,079 --> 00:12:24,755
That my body will blacken
And turn into coal

211
00:12:24,959 --> 00:12:27,473
We're getting kind of grim.

212
00:12:28,720 --> 00:12:33,510
Then I'll look from the door
Of my heavenly home

213
00:12:33,680 --> 00:12:39,152
